This guide was last updated in October 2025, and as such, sections may become outdated over time.

# Best Practices For Building A Genie Space

This guide is designed to provide a comprehensive walkthrough for configuring a Genie Space according to best practices. **The intent of this guide is to work through it in order**, implementing the features as they are relevant to the Genie Space you are creating. 

## Contents

1. **Data engineering** \- The underlying data is the foundation of your Genie Space. The more work that is pre-done, the easier the job is for Genie and the better the responses will be.  
2. **Benchmarks \-** Setting expectations and targets for your Genie Space, and evaluating its performance against them.  
3. **Metadata** \- How Genie develops its context for what data is available to it, and what it’s intended to use it for.   
4. **Joins** \- The primary way Genie learns the relationships between the data you have given to it. This is where it learns the rules for the ways it’s intended to combine data together.  
5. **SQL queries, expressions, and functions** \- Where Genie learns *how* to work with your data. This is where it will pick up patterns for how data is supposed to be manipulated and analysed. This is also where you can provide tools and building blocks for Genie to use to make its query creation process easier.  
6. **General instructions** \- For final contextual adjustments over the Genie Space. This is where you can explain the high-level purpose of the Genie Space, and the high-level lifecycles and relationships surrounding entities that Genie is covering. It’s also a good place to reinforce behaviours/rules you have specified elsewhere within your Genie Space.  
7. **Monitoring** \- Where you can leverage informed business users to identify gaps in your Genie Space, so that you can further improve your inputs.  
8. **Ongoing Maintenance** \- For monitoring the usage and performance of your Genie Space as general users interact with it and future changes are made to it, to identify if any additions need to be made or changes break existing functionality. 

# 

# 1\. Engineering your data

The underlying data used in a Genie Space should be “Gold Layer” data—cleansed, read-optimised, de-normalised data ready for an analyst to leverage. By pre-joining or flattening your data, you will eliminate computationally heavy operations from the generated queries, make them simpler and more readable, and reduce the potential for error in the generated SQL.   
Consider materialising the underlying data to improve query response times, to make your Genie Space more responsive for users.  
Pre-calculate and engineer common derived fields. This eliminates ambiguity in calculations for both Genie and end-users.  
Only include data that is relevant to the scope of your Genie Space. If there are, for example, any rows that should be consistently filtered out, that should be done during the data engineering phase, rather than as a rule for Genie to follow. Unnecessary columns can be hidden to remove potential points of confusion. 

**Actions:**

- [ ] Denormalise your data \- flatten it wherever sensible, pre-run any relevant joins.  
- [ ] Consider materialising your data to improve query runtime performance.  
- [ ] Ensure your data is human readable \- would the values be interpretable to an analyst in your organization without additional context?   
- [ ] Remove any data that should never be returned \- if data should not be returned under any context, it should be filtered out. If a column is unnecessary for the Genie Space, it should be hidden.

## Choosing between tables/views and metric views.

![][image1]  
*Creating a “Financial Year” dimension in a Metric View, means we remove any ambiguity from the term*

[Metric views](https://docs.databricks.com/aws/en/metric-views/) allow for defining a semantic layer, ensuring consistent metric calculations, and simplified queries for business users. Metric views allow you to set display names, specify formats, and define synonyms as code, making the infrastructure you develop reusable and consistent across your projects.

**Examples of fields that can be defined in metric views**

* Financial Years/Quarters   
* Involved aggregations  
* Ratios  
* Conditional statements   
* Internal definitions

**Example of a good metric**  
Rather than relying on Genie to only count rows where status \= ‘approved’ as revenue, we can create it as a simple metric for it to reference

```
measures:
  - name: total_revenue
    expr: SUM(purchase_amount) FILTER (WHERE status = 'approved')
    comment: Total revenue generated from approved purchases over a period
    display_name: Total Revenue
    format:
      type: currency
      currency_code: USD
      decimal_places:
        type: exact
        places: 2
      hide_group_separator: false
      abbreviation: compact
    synonyms:
      - revenue
      - gross revenue
      - approved revenue
```

**Actions:**

- [ ] Check if it is possible to represent your data in a metric view  
- [ ] Pre-calculate any reused dimensions or measures.

# 

# 2\. Benchmarks

Benchmarks allow you to define what success looks like for your Genie Space, allowing you to establish a target state. By creating a set of questions that represent the kinds of queries you expect users to ask, you create a reflective evaluation to test your space against as you progress through it. 

These natural language questions and queries should be written alongside subject matter experts, to ensure they are representative of the behaviours expected from an analyst over the data.

A desired output format should be specified with benchmarks, to ensure the query is evaluated fairly (unless the output formatting is part of what is being benchmarked). 

At this early stage, you should expect many of your benchmarks to fail; this is by design. These initial results act as a roadmap, to guide you as you work through the subsequent sections, adding metadata, defining joins, and teaching the Genie Space how to query over your data. By utilising the benchmarking tool, you can re-run your common queries through an automated process, providing you with a consistent and repeatable system for evaluating the state of your Genie Space.   
![][image2]  
*Because a desired output format wasn’t initially specified, manual reviews were required for the initial benchmarks. Once these had been specified in either the benchmark prompts themselves, or within the tooling of the Genie Space, manual reviews were no longer needed.*

**Actions**

- [ ] Create a set of benchmarks that cover commonly asked questions.  
- [ ] Include some challenging questions in your benchmarks \- work with subject matter experts to design these.  
- [ ] Ensure your benchmarks have a specified or desired response format so the evaluator can accurately compare the generated output to the expected result.  
- [ ] Evaluate which questions the Genie Space answers inconsistently or incorrectly to keep as reference for subsequent steps.

# 3\. Adding relevant metadata

Genie considers metadata surrounding tables and fields to provide additional context, helping direct its query generation. Metadata such as the table and column descriptions will be initially pulled from Unity Catalog. Any changes to metadata within a Genie Space do not affect the metadata in the underlying table/view/metric view in Unity Catalog, so they can be set to be Genie Space specific, without impacting other users or use cases.

## Table descriptions

Table descriptions should be used to provide a description of what the table represents, under what conditions the data within it is applicable for Genie’s usage, and any conditions or terms that apply across multiple fields of the table. 

**Example:**

| Good Table Description |  | Bad Table Description |
| ----- | :---- | ----- |
| *The scope of the table*  *When Genie should use the table*   *The lifecycle of entities within the table, and the conditions that apply to them*  *The relationship between entities in this table and the wider Genie Space* | This table covers data relating to transactions \- covering details relating to their processing progression and commercial attributes.  This is the primary table to be used for calculating figures relating to revenue, or purchases.   When a user initiates a transaction, its attributes will be added as a row in this table. A transaction will progress from ‘initiated’, to either ‘approved’ or ‘rejected’. Only approved transactions count towards revenue.   Each transaction is recorded as a single row in the table. Each individual transaction is tied to a single user, and single merchant.    | Transactions data covers data relating to transactions.   |
|  |  |  |
|  |  |  |
|  |  |  |
|  |  |  |
|  |  |  |
|  |  |  |
|  |  |  |
|  |  |  |

**Actions:**

- [ ] Add an explanation of the scope of data in the table/metric view.  
- [ ] Include conditions under which Genie should leverage this data \- the types of user questions this data can help answer.   
- [ ] Add any definitions or terms that apply across multiple fields within the table.

## Field descriptions

![][image3]  
*Metadata explaining what the given field represents, when it should be used, and other terms that may be used to refer to it.*

Field descriptions should be used to provide context over what the field represents, under what conditions the given field should be used by Genie, and any conditions or terms specific to the field.

**Actions:**

- [ ] Add an explanation of what the field represents  
- [ ] Add an explanation of under what conditions this field would be relevant to use

## Synonyms

Synonyms are a key feature for improving Genie's ability to match relevant fields to user prompts. They should be populated with terms that users may use to refer to the data within the field. This can be an excellent place to put acronyms, internal business terminology, aliases, or generalised terms that users may use to refer to specific fields. A synonym does not have to be a literal, direct synonym \- they can act as a keyword or tag that directs Genie to consider a field when a user mentions a specific term.

**Actions:**

- [ ] Consider the kinds of terms that someone in your organisation would use to refer to a field, or a term for something they would calculate directly from a field \- add them in as synonyms to the given fields.

## Example values and value dictionaries

| ℹ️ Newly created Genie Spaces will have example values and value dictionaries turned on by default. For Genie Spaces created before September 2025, please verify that example values and value dictionaries have been turned on. |
| :---- |

Example values and value dictionaries can be auto-created by Genie \- ensure they are turned on for relevant fields in your project, under Advanced options. They are used to provide the model with context as to the underlying data within the column, so that Genie is able to perform actions such as exact matches on fields. For example, if a user asks for data about “Australia”, but the value in the field is “AUS”, Genie will have the context of what the correct value in the field to match is by either looking at example values for the field, or checking potential values in the value dictionary. Example values are particularly effective on fields that follow a standardised naming convention. Value dictionaries are particularly effective on categorical fields with a large, but set number of potential values.  

**Actions:**

- [ ] Ensure Example Values and Value Dictionaries are turned on under “Advanced”.

# 

# 4\. Joins

Where sensible, data should be pre-joined to improve performance and remove ambiguity of relationships. For data where it doesn’t make sense to pre-join, the Joins tab should be used to explicitly specify the relationships between the different tables in your Genie Space, and how they can be joined together. You can either use column equality, or write a join condition in SQL code. Specifying joins allows Genie to understand the relationships between entities, and how it is supposed to create joins and aggregations when generating SQL code. Genie will respect primary key and foreign key relationships specified in Unity Catalog, but the Joins tab can be used to further enforce these behaviours.

![][image4]  
*Specifying a join, where one merchant could have many transactions associated to them (A One to Many join)*

**Actions:**

- [ ] Consider which fields can be used to join tables  
- [ ] If they are an exact match, add a column equality join  
- [ ] If there are some transformations or conditions required, add a SQL expression join.  
- [ ] Ensure to specify the relationship type correctly

# 5\. SQL queries, expressions, and functions

## SQL queries

SQL queries should be added as examples for Genie to reference. Example Queries include the corresponding natural language question, providing Genie with context on when these queries should be used. Queries can be parameterized, to give reference to Genie as to which values should be substituted under different conditions. Genie can directly use these example queries \- either whole, or as part of a larger query, providing it with templates to leverage. Additionally, Genie can generalise over the example queries given to it \- picking up on attributes like coding patterns and output formatting. It is worth running the Genie Space’s benchmarks at this stage, to evaluate which questions it still fails to answer, or answers inconsistently, to identify which aspects of the generated SQL could be enhanced through example queries.

![][image5]  
*A paramaterised “building block” query, that would be used as a part/reference for other queries about revenue.*

**Actions:**

- [ ] Run the Genie Space’s benchmarks to identify which queries and aspects of queries the Genie Space struggles with.  
- [ ] Consider what the commonly asked questions will be in your Genie Space, and add them as Example Queries.  
- [ ] Identify the 'building blocks' of your queries and add them as Example Queries. These are reusable components such as Common Table Expressions (CTEs), standard calculations, or complex filtering logic.  
- [ ] Ensure your Example Queries follow any rules/conditions you’ve specified in descriptions, joins, etc. Do not contradict statements or break rules specified elsewhere in your Genie Space.  
- [ ] Match the design patterns and desired output formatting in your example queries to the style you want Genie to return data to you.

## SQL Expressions

SQL Expressions allow you to define common business concepts as reusable SQL snippets. Unlike full Example Queries, these are smaller, modular pieces of logic that Genie can use as building blocks when constructing a query. These are particularly useful for Genie Spaces that are built over tables, rather than over metric views, as they allow you to specify internal logic explicitly \- a feature already inherent to metric views. 

You can define three types of expressions:

* **Filters:** Boolean conditions that are often used in a `WHERE` clause (e.g., `status = 'approved'` or `use_case_status = 'active'`).  
* **Dimensions:** Row-level calculations that create a new value from existing columns (e.g., calculating a financial year from a date `CASE WHEN MONTH(transaction_date) >= 7 THEN...` or `DATE_TRUNC('month', created_date)`).  
* **Measures:** Aggregations that calculate a value over multiple rows (e.g., `SUM(price * units)` or `AVG(cash_back_amount)`).

By defining these concepts explicitly, you provide Genie with clear, reusable components. This helps ensure consistency in calculations, simplifies complex logic, and improves Genie's ability to construct queries that match your own methods and terminology.

Each expression allows you to add:

* **Synonyms:** Common terms users might use to refer to this concept.  
* **Instructions:** Specific guidance on how and when Genie should use (or avoid using) this expression.

**Actions:**

- [ ] Identify common, repeated logic in your queries, such as standard filters, case statements, or calculations.  
- [ ] Create SQL Expressions for these snippets, separating them into Filters, Dimensions, and Measures.  
- [ ] Populate the **Synonyms** field with business terminology (e.g., "active users," "total sales," "current quarter") to improve natural language matching.  
- [ ] Use the **Instructions** field to provide clear rules, e.g., "Only use this filter when the user asks for 'active' customers" or "This measure represents gross revenue, not net."

## Functions

SQL functions can be added as tools that Genie can run to give consistent outputs. These are [UDFs](https://docs.databricks.com/aws/en/udf/) (User-defined functions) with specified inputs and outputs, to ensure that a given set of inputs always follow an exact, hardcoded formula. They should be used for outputs that do not need to be generalised, that follow a very specifically defined method of generation, based on specified inputs. Genie applies the 'Trusted' tag to responses generated from SQL Functions, to allow users to know they are following a pre-specified template.   
![][image6]  
*GST calculations follow a specific formula, which can be written in a UDF, ensuring calculations are performed consistently, rather than running from generated SQL.* 

**Actions:**

- [ ] Consider which functions Genie should be able to repeat, without any alterations, only by passing in parameters.  
- [ ] Create UDFs for these functions, and add them as SQL functions to the Genie Space.

# 6\. General instructions

![][image7]  
*These general instructions provide a high level overview of the scope of the Genie Space, the scope of each table, the relationships between the entities covered in the Genie Space, how the entities evolve, and reinforce rules specified in example queries, joins, and table/column descriptions.*

Before writing any general instructions, **test your Genie Space in its current state** \- you should use this process to identify contextual gaps in your Genie Space. Use the observed gaps in the responses returned by Genie to identify the most appropriate place to adjust your Genie Space from the features previously implemented.

Here’s a table of some common issues, and solutions:

| Gap | Area To Check | Changes |
| :---: | ----- | ----- |
| **Query uses the wrong fields**  | Column Descriptions Synonyms | Ensure your column descriptions cover the context of your question. Use the keywords from the query that specify the columns you want to be used in the synonyms for that field.  |
| **An underlying calculation is incorrect** | Metric view dimensions or measures Example Queries SQL Functions  | Can the calculations be pre-done in metric views? Make a sample query with the exact aspect of the calculation that was performed incorrectly. If the calculation doesn’t need to be generalised, would it be better served as a SQL function? |
| **Says there’s not sufficient data to answer a question, when enough data is available in the Genie Space** | Table Descriptions Synonyms | Ensure the table description specifies that the table covers this use case. Ensure the keywords from the question are included in the synonyms for the relevant fields Genie should be using.  |
| **Attempts to give an answer for data that’s not in the Genie Space**  | Table Descriptions | Ensure the table descriptions explain the scope of what the tables cover without ambiguity. |
| **Answers the same question inconsistently** | Example Queries SQL Functions | Add an example query of the given question with parameters as a template for Genie to use Add the template as a SQL Function to remove any ambiguity or interpretation from the outputs.  |
| **The format returned isn’t ideal** | Example Queries Field descriptions | Ensure your Example Queries match to the format you want your outputs to be given in Specify in the field descriptions when you want the given field to be returned |

If, after refining the Genie Space, it still displays contextual gaps, then this context should be added to the general instructions. The context in general instructions should be given with the desired outcome behaviour from Genie in mind—ensure they guide Genie towards a specific action or behavioural pattern. General instructions are not intended to be the primary source of truth for Genie—they should only be leveraged as a reference to guide it, not the primary way to enforce behaviours.

Finally, general instructions can be used to add high-level context to a Genie Space. This can include a high-level overview of the purpose of the Genie Space that analysts will be using it for, an explanation of the scope that is covered within the Genie Space, broken down by applicable topics, and a high-level, human-readable explanation of the relationship between these topics. 

**Example:**

| Good General Instructions | Bad General Instructions |  |
| ----- | ----- | :---- |
| This covers analysis of transactions and cash-back rewards given to consumers for making purchases with relevant merchants.  Customers receive cash-back on their purchase for making purchases with given vendors. A single customer can make multiple purchases with multiple vendors.  A customer has associated account and demographic information. A customer needs to be accepted on the platform in order to receive cash-back on their purchases.  A merchant will have an associated industry and base cash-back rate. A single merchant can have multiple customers, each making multiple purchases. A transaction will have associated purchase and in-house processing progression information. A transaction will progress from pending, to either rejected or approved. Each individual transaction will have a single associated customer and vendor.  Rejected transactions do not count towards cash-back or revenue.   | \*\* CRITICAL: ALWAYS JOIN LOWER(merchants.id) \= LOWER(transactions.merchant\_id) \*\*   ACRONYMS: MAU: Monthly active users AU: Activated users CB: Cash back   If rejected is not specified as a condition, please only use approved. similar for accepted.  Use these fiscal quarter range definitions for dates q1: July–September (E.g., fy-2024 q1 \= Jul–Sep 2023\) q2: October–December (E.g., fy-2024 q2 \= Oct–Dec 2023\) q3: January–March (E.g., fy-2024 q3 \= Jan–Mar 2024\) q4: April–June (E.g., fy-2024 q4 \= Apr–Jun 2024\)  For cash back percent, this is defined as sum(cash\_back) / sum(purchase\_amount)  Always exclude merchants.status \= ‘deactivated’ | *This join should be covered in the Joins section, instead of in the General Instructions. The key join condition should be fixed during data modeling. Acronyms should be included in the field descriptions and synonyms where they are relevant. These ones also don’t have any context as to what they apply to or represent.  It’s not clear as to which columns these rules apply to, or under what conditions. They would almost certainly be better off entirely re-worked as metrics, or at a minimum given in the column descriptions themselves.  These should instead be engineered fields in the underlying data, to remove any ambiguity or accountability from the generated queries. These would be a well-suited use case for a dimension in a metric view. These should be given as measures in a metric view. At a minimum, these should be covered as example queries. This exclusion should be done at the data engineering level, rather than a condition to always be added in to generated queries.*  |

**Actions**

- [ ] Test your Genie Space before adding general instructions \- run the Genie Space’s benchmarks, and interact with the space as an analyst  
- [ ] See if gaps can be fixed using tooling in the Genie Space other than the general instructions  
- [ ] Add general instructions for gaps that cannot be filled using other tooling  
- [ ] Add a high-level overview of the scope of the Genie Space, and relationships between topics to the general instructions

# 

# 7\. Monitoring 

After holistic testing and refinement, provide access to your Genie Space to a small number of subject matter experts for the topic it covers. Instruct them to provide feedback in the Genie Space using the provided rating tooling. Reviewers can leave written comments to provide feedback to assist you in refining the Genie Space.

**Iterative pattern for improving a Genie Space using Monitoring**

1. A subject matter expert (SME) will start with a specific natural language question and target output in mind.  
2. They will converse back and forth with Genie until they arrive at their desired output, which they can mark as “Good.”  
3. The final, correct output SQL query can be added as an Example Query with their original natural language question.  
4. The gaps displayed during the iterative process can be used to guide further refinements to the Genie Space.

Inform the SMEs they should feel free to iteratively refine their questions or heavily guide Genie into getting the right answer \- it’s still under development, and this phase is intended to guide refinement and identify the existing gaps of the Genie Space. They should mark “Bad” the incorrect queries and mark “Good” final, correct answer queries. 

For leveraging the findings of “Bad” queries, cover the same table as the “General instructions” section, with the additional points of:

| Gap | Area to Check | Changes |
| ----- | ----- | ----- |
| **The user asks questions about data that’s outside of the scope of the Genie Space** | Genie Space Description Data | Specify in the description (Which is intended for users) what the Genie Space covers, and doesn’t cover. If the data makes sense to include in the Genie Space, can it be added in?  |
| **It takes multiple steps for the user to get to an answer they want to arrive at in one step** | Example Queries | Add the final, “Good” query to the Example Queries along with the user’s original question. |

If a Genie Space seems to be giving an excessive amount of bad responses, it may be worth fundamentally re-assessing the scope and purpose of the Genie Space \- from the original underlying data foundations. 

![][image8]  
*A subject matter expert has iterated through queries with Genie until arriving at their desired outcome. They have marked “Bad” the queries that had issues, and marked “Good” the query that arrived at the result they were looking for.*

**Actions**

- [ ] Get a small number of SMEs (Subject matter experts) to use the Genie Space, and mark “Good” good responses, mark “Bad” incorrect queries/undesired responses  
- [ ] Refine the Genie Space based on their feedback  
- [ ] Add verified, “Good” responses as Example Queries

# 

# 8\. Ongoing Maintenance

To ensure the long-term success and relevance of your Genie Space, you will need to monitor its usage and performance as people interact with it. This ongoing maintenance will allow you to identify if new additions are needed, and importantly to ensure that future changes don’t break existing functionality. 

## Monitoring Tab

The primary tool for understanding how your Genie Space is being used is the Monitoring Tab. Regularly reviewing this will provide you with insights into user behaviour. Look for common questions that are being asked, identify areas where the Genie Space is struggling, and note any queries that are inconsistent or incorrect. This data will guide you to focus your efforts, whether it’s adding new metadata, refining joins, creating new example queries, or adjusting the general instructions to better support users’ needs.

## Benchmarks

As you make improvements, your benchmark suite becomes your primary tool for quality assurance. Benchmarks should be run to quickly evaluate if changes made to a Genie Space had a positive or negative impact on its overall performance. For example, after adding in a new data source, re-running your benchmarks is the fastest way to check if the new data has added ambiguity or confusion to the contextual understanding of the Genie Space. If you see a drop in performance, you can use the benchmark results to evaluate what needs to be fixed to resolve any regressions.

**Actions**

- [ ] Regularly check the Monitoring Tab to understand how your Genie Space is being used and identify areas for improvement.  
- [ ] Whenever major changes are made to the Genie Space (e.g., a new data source is added), re-run your benchmarks to ensure you haven't negatively impacted existing functionality.  
- [ ] Use insights from user queries and benchmark results to adjust the Genie Space accordingly, ensuring it continues to meet user expectations.
